Prompt Engineering Using Google Gemini

Arijitraha on 2025-01-12

In this article, I will show you systematically how to create a chatbot using prompts from Google Gemini. Such chatbot will be able to generate text response from multimodal inputs — which includes both text and images.

Cool !

Let’s understand Gemini. Google Gemini is a family of advanced AI models developed by Google DeepMind. These models are designed to understand and generate human-like text, code, images, audio. For instance, if you ask Gemini to draft an email, it can produce a well-structured message based on your brief instructions.

Gemini API: An API is a set of rules and protocols that allows different software applications to communicate with each other. It defines the methods and data formats that programs can use to request and exchange information. Think of an API as a menu in a restaurant: Menu lists the dishes (services) you can order. Order Process is when you place an order (request) specifying what you want. Kitchen is where you prepare the dish (processes the request). And, finally, Waiter brings the dish to your table (response). You don’t need to know how the kitchen operates; you just use the menu to get what you want. Similarly, developers use or call APIs to access specific functionalities without understanding the internal workings of the software. The Gemini API is a set of endpoints that provides access to Google’s generative models, including the Gemini family of models.

All good, now few lines about Google Gemini and OpenAI's ChatGPT. Gemini provides a secure and ethical interactions which is suited for sensitive task — I will show how this security and ethical aspects are established with python codes from my work done in Google Colab— and it is specialized for multi-modal capabilities as well. ChatGPT, on the other hand is specialized for text-based task and research. Not to forget that at the heart of the LLM revolution is Open AI’s Chat Generative Pre-trained Transformer (ChatGPT). And, close on its heels is Google Gemini. See, both are good and are constantly evolving — that’s the good part of things !!

Now, before I go ahead implementing Gemini using Python, it is super important to understand this: It’s not that chatbot were not build earlier to the advent of ChatGPT. I have used traditional machine learning and deep learning models to build chatbot. However, that said, the understanding of context have improved multi-fold with the advent of attention mechanism and transformer architecture — indeed a breakthrough in the world of AI. Installing and Importing Required Libraries

pip install -q -U google-generativeai

  • Installs the google-generativeai library, which provides tools to interact with Google's generative AI models.
  • -q: Quiet mode (suppresses unnecessary output).
  • -U: Updates the library if it’s already installed.

import pathlib

  • Imports the pathlib module, which simplifies file and directory handling across operating systems.

import textwrap

  • Provides tools to manipulate text formatting, such as wrapping text to a specified width.

import google.generativeai as genai

  • Imports the Google Generative AI library and assigns it the alias genai for easier use in the code.

from google.colab import userdata

  • Imports utilities from Google Colab to manage user data (relevant only when running in Google Colab).

from IPython.display import display, Markdown

  • Allows rendering of rich content like Markdown in Jupyter notebooks (or Google Colab).

Markdown Conversion Function

def to_markdown(text):

  • Defines a function to_markdown to convert plain text into Markdown format.

text = text.replace('.', ' *')

  • Replaces every period (.) in the text with * to add some Markdown-specific formatting.

return Markdown(textwrap.indent(text, '> ', predicate=lambda _: True))

  • Indents each line of the text with > to format it as a Markdown blockquote.

Configuring API Keys

import os

  • Imports the os module, which allows interaction with the operating system.

os.environ['GOOGLE_API_KEY'] = "AIzaSyA8...nononoplz"

  • Sets the GOOGLE_API_KEY environment variable to the given API key. This key is required to authenticate requests to Google's generative AI service.

genai.configure(api_key="AIzaSyA8...nononoplz")

  • Configures the google-generativeai library with the provided API key.

genai.configure(api_key=os.environ['GOOGLE_API_KEY'])

  • Reconfigures the API key by retrieving it from the environment variable. This ensures consistency and security.

Listing Available Models

for m in genai.list_models():

  • Iterates through the list of all models available via the API.

if 'generateContent' in m.supported_generation_methods:

  • Filters models that support the generateContent method (used for text generation).

print(m.name)

  • Prints the name of each model that meets the above criteria.

Selecting a Model

model = genai.GenerativeModel('gemini-pro')

  • Selects the gemini-pro model for generating content.

model

  • Displays information about the selected model.

Generating Content

%%time

  • A Jupyter notebook magic command to measure the time taken to execute the cell.

response = model.generate_content("How to make a sandwich")

  • Asks the model to generate content based on the prompt “How to make a sandwich”.

to_markdown(response.text)

  • Formats the generated text into Markdown and displays it.

response.prompt_feedback

  • Retrieves feedback information about the prompt-response pair.

response.candidates

  • Lists all response candidates generated by the model.

Now, stream response — Streaming delivers output incrementally, similar to watching a movie as it downloads.

Streaming Response

response = model.generate_content("Tell me something about Virat Kohli", stream=True)

  • Asks the model to generate content with streaming enabled (chunks of the response are delivered progressively).

for chunk in response:

  • Iterates through chunks of the response.

print(chunk.text)

  • Prints the text of each chunk.

print("_" * 80)

  • Prints a line of underscores to separate chunks visually.

Let’s generates text description from image: By combining text and images, the system demonstrates its ability to process multiple modalities simultaneously.

Note that I have used snipping tool to capture the response from colab in small cuts for better visibility.

Image-Based Prompt

import PIL.Image

  • Imports the Python Imaging Library (PIL) for handling image files.

bk = PIL.Image.open('image.jpg')

  • Opens an image file named image.jpg.

model = genai.GenerativeModel(model_name="gemini-1.5-pro")

  • Switches to the gemini-1.5-pro model.

prompt = "Write a description based on the image."

  • Specifies a text prompt for generating content related to the image.

response = model.generate_content([prompt, bk])

  • Sends both the text prompt and the image to the model for content generation.

print(response.text)

  • Prints the generated text based on the image.
